"Abstract A group of at least three German hackers worked, without clear discovery, for years for the Moscow secret service KGB. This is the first known case in which the KGB have used hackers for espionage. The KGB was given passwords of top secret computer systems all round the world. It is also known that high-tech computer software and data were copied for the KGB. Named victims of the hackers activity are computer systems of the Pentagon in Washington DC, Atom i.e. research laboratories in Los Alamos, the French armament concern Thompson, CERN and other high-tech firms and scientific institutes in Western Europe, North America, and Japan. In August 1989 the Federal Public prosecutor charged the hackers and two contact persons or agents with espionage. This article reviews the case and considers the implications."
